text.text:
I'm a big fan of Sticks & Sushi and have been to several of their locations, all of which have received 5-star reviews from me. However, the Covent Garden branch seems to consistently underperform compared to the others.

The food itself is still very good. The sushi platter we ordered was excellent - fresh, flavorful, and beautifully presented. The quality of the ingredients and preparation is on par with what I've experienced at their other restaurants.

However, the service is really where this location falls short. The server seemed more focused on socializing with their coworkers than attending to our table. It took a very long time to get our order taken, get refills, and even get the bill. They just didn't seem engaged or interested in providing a good customer experience.

While the pricing is consistent across Sticks & Sushi locations, the poor service here just doesn't live up to the standard I expect from this restaurant group. The food is still great, but the lack of attentive service drags down the overall experience.

Overall, I'd rate this particular Sticks & Sushi location a 3 out of 5. The food is still top-notch, but the service issues are hard to overlook. I'll continue visiting their other London locations, but I'd be hesitant to come back to this Covent Garden branch unless I hear the service has improved.

text.text: The most disappointing among London‚Äôs √ºber-omakases. Everything feels surprisingly chaotic considering the impeccable pedigree; the space is soulless, the team are friendly but awkward, and the food itself is solid if unmemorable. While the sushi is firmly mid-pack among its compatriots - doing nothing wrong but also nothing spectacular - the cooked items were extremely traditional and lacking in flair. Everything could do with a polish and some soul-searching to really elevate the obvious underlying quality, but at present it‚Äôs just not there. That it‚Äôs also the most expensive Japanese in London leaves one asking - why?

text.text:
Brilliant outpost for the world renowned Sushi Kanesaka in Ginza, Tokyo. Outstanding quality of fish, selected from the best in the world of the season (our tuna was from Portugal)

The experience leave you wanting more and is definitely a contributing factor to our impulse Japan trip booking. Even the post-meal fruit selection was of exceptional quality. We had the best mango one can imagine (and probably 10x better!!!)

It is pricy but, less pricy than flights to Japan (you also won‚Äôt need to take leave or book hotels!) It‚Äôs like a little taste of Japan without the effort of long haul flights, truly the best you can get in London. Will for sure visit their original Ginza location soon.

The place is just a show.  Located on the 39th, 40th floor. Spectacular view is reflected.  The design is luxurious, meticulous and elegant and so is the service.
The most beautiful and clean toilets I have ever seen :)
Reservations are required in advance, and we sat on the bar floor, which is smaller and more intimate.  I recommend ordering on the restaurant floor, the atmosphere is much better there and there is also an amazing balcony!
The sushi and salad were excellent and served beautifully on the plate.  The lamb was not successful.
The prices are very expensive.
It was a good experience for sure.

text.text: First time visiting and definitely lived up to expectations, this place is definitely upscale, it's not a casual wear jeans and trainers establishment, they can refuse access based on your attire, so check before you attend. It is also not a budget friendly so don't expect a cheap bill unless your drinking tap water. The overall decor is beautiful, the views are of course breathtaking literally from the height! The staff, the food, the music, was amazing! I will definitely be going back to try the main restaurant, a special thanks to Alioune &  Vuole, made the experience so enjoyable! Thank you!

text.text:
We had the Yuzu Salted Edamame and two omakase sushi set. A plate of 15 pieces of sushi was served all at once. The quality of the sushi was overall good, and the cocktails were nice, especially the Sweet Tokyo (whisky-based cocktails).

It‚Äôs hard to find similar sushi quality in London at this price range, but I suggest better control of hygiene.  I saw a fly over the sushi (not on our plate) right in front of us, and it seemed the chefs noticed it too, as I believed they did not serve that plate to the client.  It would be a good idea to keep the door closed to prevent flies from entering the restaurant.
